15 homeland, the State of Israel, underscoring the persistent and dangerous threat of
16 antisemitism worldwide; and
17 WHEREAS, the Georgia General Assembly took a critical step in combating antisemitism
18 by passing House Bill 30 during the previous legislative session, formally adopting the
19 International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance (IHRA) definition of antisemitism into
20 Georgia law; and
21 WHEREAS, despite this progress, it is imperative that Georgia lawmakers remain vigilant
22 and proactive in addressing antisemitism in our schools, communities, and public institutions,
23 ensuring that hate and intolerance have no place in this state; and
24 WHEREAS, the observance of International Holocaust Remembrance Day is not only a time
25 for reflection but also a call to action to combat contemporary forms of antisemitism and
26 safeguard the rights and dignity of all people.
27 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE that the members of this body
28 recognize January 27, 2025, as International Holocaust Remembrance Day in Georgia, honor
29 the memory of the victims of the Holocaust, condemn all forms of antisemitism and hate, and
30 reaffirm the commitment to fostering a state that stands firmly against prejudice and
31 discrimination.
32 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Secretary of the Senate is authorized and directed
33 to make appropriate copies of this resolution available for distribution to the public and the
34 press.
